  "prompt": "How much money did each candidate spend in the 1912 election?",
  "response": "In the 1912 United States presidential election, campaign finance records were not as detailed or systematically recorded as they are today. However, there are estimates of approximately how much each of the main candidates spent during their campaigns:\n\n1. **Woodrow Wilson (Democratic Party)**: Wilson's campaign is estimated to have spent about $1.1 million.\n\n2. **Theodore Roosevelt (Progressive \"Bull Moose\" Party)**: Roosevelt's campaign is estimated to have spent around $2.5 million. His candidacy was notable because he ran as a third-party candidate after serving previously as a Republican president.\n\n3. **William Howard Taft (Republican Party)**: Taft's campaign is estimated to have spent about $1.1 million. He was the incumbent president at the time.\n\n4. **Eugene V. Debs (Socialist Party)**: Debs' campaign expenditures were significantly lower, roughly around $66,000.\n\nThese figures are approximations and reflect the less formal campaign finance documentation standards of the early 20th century.",
